		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">This research proposal concerns the investigation of the pyro- and piezo-electric properties of chiral liquid-crystalline polymers, and is a collaborative programme between the School of  Chemistry at the University of Hull and the School of Electronic Engineering at the University College of North Wales.  The objectives of the proposed programme are to design, synthesise and characterise a novel range of ferroelectric liquid crystal polymers at Hull, and to align the materials and investigate and correlate their physical properties at Bangor.  The fact that the polymers will be designed to exhibit ferroelectric smectic phases means that they will also show pyroelectric properties.  Ferroelectric properties are created in these systems by incorporating asymmetric centres into the polymer structure thereby making the polymer chiral.  The magnitude of the ferro- and pyro-effects are determined by the nature and environment of the asymmetric centre(s).  Thus the objectives of the proposal are as follows:  1) to synthesise novel polymers that exhibit ferroelectric liquid crystal phases in suitable temperature ranges for investigation of their physical properties;  2) to systematically very the structures of the polymers so that a number of liquid crystal properties can be correlated with structure, eg transition temperatures, Tg etc;  3) to systematically change and vary the number and location of the chiral points in the polymer, so as to affect the physical properties of the material; 4) to correlate pyroelectric and piezoelectric properties with molecular structure; 5) to develop new methods of aligning liquid crystal polymers; and 6) to design polymers that internally compensate for the helical structures that sometimes occur in ferroelectric liquid crystal phases.  The long term goals of this work are to create a new class of pyro- and piezo- electric polymers that have physical properties that are superior to those of currently available organic polymers, such as PVDF and related systems.  Another important long term objective is to create self-assembling pyroelectric systems that can be easily processed to give relatively thin, ordered films.  Advances of this nature could give industry access to a low cost, highly sensitive materials for use in a wide range of applications such as pyroelectric detectors and sensors.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
